'Aren't you cold?' asked his mother when the road turned toward the river and a gust of wind set up a downy ripple in the gray bird's wing of her hat. 'Yes, I am,' said her son, looking at the river. His mother with a mewing sound was about to reach out and arrange his cloak, but noticing the look in his eye she swiftly snatched her hand back and merely indicated with a twiddle of her fingers in mid-air: 'Close it up, close it tighter.' The boy did not stir. Pur